<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-inscribed-circles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Inscribed Circles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Construct an inscribed, circumscribed and escribed circles on a triangle</li>
                              <li>Determine the centroid and orthocentre of a triangle</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To guide learners to discover the incenter by asking: <em>what is the largest circle that fits inside a triangle?</em> Learners experiment with circle placement, then reason their way to the angle bisector construction.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Resist giving the answer to part (a). Let learners place the centre intuitively first — most will not choose the same point, which makes part (b) productive.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>The Largest Circle Inside a Triangle</title>
                <p>
                    In this activity you will investigate where to place a circle so that it fits inside a triangle as large as possible.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a triangle <m>ABC</m> of your choice using a ruler (no need for a specific size). Using a compass, try to draw the largest circle you can that fits <em>completely inside</em> the triangle — the circle must not cross any side. Mark the centre you used and record the radius.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Compare your circle with a classmate's. Did you choose the same centre? Who has the larger radius? Try adjusting your centre to see if you can do better.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Think about why the best centre must be <em>equidistant from all three sides</em>. If the circle is closer to one side than the others, explain why you could shift the centre slightly to increase the radius.
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    If the distance to one side is less than the distance to another, the circle's radius is limited by the nearest side. Shifting the centre away from the nearest side (while staying away from the other two) increases the minimum distance, allowing a larger circle. The optimal centre is where all three distances are equal.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Can you find a method to always construct the best centre, no matter what triangle you start with?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the incenter construction and introduce the inradius formula <m>r = \Delta/s</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Emphasise that the incenter is always inside the triangle (unlike the circumcenter, which can be outside for obtuse triangles).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Present the key formula: the triangle can be cut into three smaller triangles by joining <m>I</m> to each vertex. Each has a side of the original triangle as its base and <m>r</m> as its height, giving <m>\Delta = r \cdot s</m>, so <m>r = \Delta/s</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

     <paragraphs>
        <title>Constructing the Inscribed Circle</title>
        <p>
            To construct the inscribed circle of a triangle using only a pair of compasses and a straightedge, follow these steps.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw triangle <m>ABC</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step1">
                        <caption>Step 1: Triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/-1/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Bisect angle <m>A</m>: place the compass point at <m>A</m> and draw an arc that crosses both sides <m>AB</m> and <m>AC</m>. Label the crossing points <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step2">
                        <caption>Step 2: Arc from <m>A</m> crossing sides <m>AB</m> at <m>P</m> and <m>AC</m> at <m>Q</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/-1/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(A,1.5) \tkzGetPoints{X}{P}
                                    \tkzInterLC[R](A,C)(A,1.5) \tkzGetPoints{Y}{Q}
                                    \tkzCompasss[red](A,P A,Q)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(P,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Without changing the compass width, place the compass point at <m>P</m> and draw an arc inside the triangle. Then place the compass point at <m>Q</m> and draw a crossing arc. Draw the ray from <m>A</m> to the meeting of these arcs, and extend it until it meets <m>BC</m>. This ray bisects angle <m>A</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step3">
                        <caption>Step 3: Arcs from <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> meet at <m>D</m>; ray <m>AD</m> bisects angle <m>A</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                             <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/-1/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(A,1.5) \tkzGetPoints{X}{P}
                                    \tkzInterLC[R](A,C)(A,1.5) \tkzGetPoints{Y}{Q}
                                    \tkzDefLine[bisector, normed](B,A,C) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                                    \tkzInterLL(a,A)(B,C) \tkzGetPoint{M_A}
                                    \tkzShowLine[bisector,gap=2.5,size=1.5,color=red](B,A,C)
                                    \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](A,M_A)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(P,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Repeat the same process for angle <m>B</m>: draw an arc from <m>B</m> crossing sides <m>BA</m> and <m>BC</m>, then draw crossing arcs to find a point, and draw the bisector ray from <m>B</m>. Label the point where the two bisector rays meet as <m>I</m> — this is the <term>incenter</term>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step4">
                        <caption>Step 4: Bisectors of angles <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> meet at the incenter <m>I</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/-1/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                    \tkzDefLine[bisector, normed](B,A,C) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                                    \tkzInterLL(a,A)(B,C) \tkzGetPoint{M_A}
                                    \tkzShowLine[bisector,gap=2.5,size=1.5,color=red](B,A,C)

                                    \tkzDefLine[bisector, normed](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                                    \tkzInterLL(b,B)(A,C) \tkzGetPoint{M_B}
                                    \tkzShowLine[bisector,gap=2.5,size=1.5,color=red](A,B,C)

                                    \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](A,M_A B,M_B)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        From <m>I</m>, drop a perpendicular to one side of the triangle (for example, to side <m>BC</m>). To do this with a compass: place the compass at <m>I</m> and draw arcs crossing <m>BC</m> on both sides; then bisect the segment between the two crossing points to find the foot. Label the foot <m>X</m>. The distance <m>IX</m> is the inradius <m>r</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step5">
                        <caption>Step 5: Perpendicular from <m>I</m> to side <m>BC</m>, with foot <m>X</m>. The length <m>IX = r</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/-1/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                    \tkzInterLC[R](B,C)(I, 2) \tkzGetPoints{Y}{Z}
                                    \tkzCompasss[red](I,Y I,Z)
                                    \tkzShowLine[mediator,color=red,length=0.5](Y,Z) \tkzGetPoints{i}{j}
                                    \tkzDrawLine[add=0.4 and 1.5, dashed](I,X)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](X)
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Set your compass to radius <m>r = IX</m>. Place the compass point at <m>I</m> and draw the circle. This circle touches all three sides of the triangle and is the inscribed circle.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step6">
                        <caption>Step 6: The completed inscribed circle with centre <m>I</m> and radius <m>r</m>, tangent to all three sides.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/-1/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](X)
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <insight>
        <p>
            The <term>inscribed circle</term> (or <term>incircle</term>) is the largest circle that fits inside a triangle, touching all three sides.
        </p>
        <p>
            Its radius is called the <term>inradius</term>, and its center is the <term>incenter</term>.
        </p>
        <p>
            To construct the inscribed circle of <m>\triangle ABC</m>, you should:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the incenter <m>I</m> by intersecting two angle bisectors.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Drop a perpendicular from <m>I</m> to any side to find the inradius <m>r</m> by marking two points on any side that are equidistant from <m>I</m>, and perpendicularly bisecting them.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>


    <theorem xml:id="thm-inscribed-circle">
        <title>The Incircle and Inradius</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The value of the inradius <m>r</m> of a triangle is given by:
                <md>
                    r = \frac{\Delta}{s},
                </md>
                where <m>s = \tfrac{1}{2}(a+b+c)</m> is the semi-perimeter of the triangle and <m>\Delta</m> is the area of the triangle.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-theorem">
                <caption>Triangle <m>ABC</m> with its inscribed circle.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1/4/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](I)\tkzGetPoint{Y}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](I)\tkzGetPoint{Z}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X I,Y I,Z)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,Y,A)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,Z,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,X,Y,Z)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](I)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Join <m>I</m> to each vertex, dividing triangle <m>ABC</m> into three smaller triangles: <m>\triangle IBC</m>, <m>\triangle ICA</m>, and <m>\triangle IAB</m>. 
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-theorem-proof">
                <caption>Triangle <m>ABC</m> with its inscribed circle.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1/4/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](I)\tkzGetPoint{Y}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](I)\tkzGetPoint{Z}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X I,Y I,Z)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[purple](I,A I,B I,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,Y,A)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,Z,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,X,Y,Z)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](I)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
                
                Because <m>I</m> is the incenter, the perpendicular height of each of these smaller triangles is <m>r</m>. Since <m>\Delta = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{base} \times \text{height}</m>, the area of each smaller triangle can be expressed as:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\Delta_{IBC} \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} a r</mrow>
                    <mrow>\Delta_{ICA} \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} b r</mrow>
                    <mrow>\Delta_{IAB} \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} c r</mrow>
                </md>
                Adding these and using <m>s = \tfrac{1}{2}(a+b+c)</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow> \Delta \amp = \Delta_{IBC} + \Delta_{ICA} + \Delta_{IAB} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \tfrac{1}{2} a r + \tfrac{1}{2} b r + \tfrac{1}{2} c r </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \tfrac{1}{2}r(a+b+c) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = r \cdot s. </mrow>
                </md>
                Dividing both sides by <m>s</m> gives <m>r = \frac{\Delta}{s}</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </theorem>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>The Centroid</title>
        <p>
            A <term>median</term> of a triangle is a line segment joining a vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side. Every triangle has three medians, and they always meet at a single point called the <term>centroid</term>, usually labelled <m>G</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-centroid-triangle">
            <caption>Triangle <m>ABC</m> with its three medians meeting at the centroid <m>G</m>. Each median joins a vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side.</caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1/4/A}
                        \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                        \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{M_a}
                        \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{M_b}
                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{M_c}
                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{G}
                        \tkzDrawSegments[teal, thick](A,M_a B,M_b C,M_c)
                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,M_a,M_b,M_c,G)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below](M_a)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[right](M_b)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](M_c)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above, xshift=2pt](G)
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            The centroid has a special property: it divides each median in the ratio <m>2:1</m> from the vertex. So if the median from <m>A</m> has length <m>m_a</m>, then <m>AG = \tfrac{2}{3}m_a</m> and <m>GM_a = \tfrac{1}{3}m_a</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Physically, the centroid is the <em>balance point</em> of the triangle: a uniform triangular lamina (flat plate) would balance on a pin placed exactly at <m>G</m>. The centroid is always inside the triangle, regardless of whether the triangle is acute, right, or obtuse.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>The Orthocentre</title>
        <p>
            An <term>altitude</term> of a triangle is the perpendicular from a vertex to the line containing the opposite side. The three altitudes of a triangle always meet at a single point called the <term>orthocentre</term>, usually labelled <m>H</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-orthocentre-triangle">
            <caption>An acute triangle <m>ABC</m> with its three altitudes meeting at the orthocentre <m>H</m>. Right-angle marks show each altitude is perpendicular to the opposite side.</caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2/4/A}
                        \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[ortho](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{H}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](A)\tkzGetPoint{Ha}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--C](B)\tkzGetPoint{Hb}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](C)\tkzGetPoint{Hc}
                        \tkzDrawSegments[teal, thick](A,Ha B,Hb C,Hc)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](A,Ha,C)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](B,Hb,C)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](C,Hc,B)
                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,H,Ha,Hb,Hc)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above, xshift=3pt](H)
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            The position of <m>H</m> depends on the type of triangle:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In an <em>acute triangle</em>, <m>H</m> lies <em>inside</em> the triangle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In a <em>right triangle</em>, <m>H</m> is at the <em>vertex of the right angle</em> (the two legs are themselves altitudes).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In an <em>obtuse triangle</em>, <m>H</m> lies <em>outside</em> the triangle, on the far side of the obtuse vertex.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has sides <m>3</m> cm, <m>4</m> cm, and <m>5</m> cm. Draw the inscribed circle, and find its radius.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-3-4-5">
                <caption>The <m>3</m>-<m>4</m>-<m>5</m> right triangle with its inscribed circle of radius <m>r = 1</m> cm.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$3$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$4$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$5$ cm}
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Drawing the incircle using the steps outlined above, we get:
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-3-4-5-drawn">
                <caption>The <m>3</m>-<m>4</m>-<m>5</m> right triangle with its inscribed circle of radius <m>r = 1</m> cm.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$3$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$4$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$5$ cm}
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawLines[dashed, add=0 and 0.5](B,I C,I A,I)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[teal](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using the inradius formula from <xref ref="thm-inscribed-circle"/>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>s \amp= \frac{3+4+5}{2} = 6 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\Delta \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} \times 3 \times 4 = 6 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp= \frac{\Delta}{s} = \frac{6}{6} = 1 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="heron-incircle">
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    In <xref ref="thm-inscribed-circle"/>, we showed that the inradius of a triangle <m>ABC</m> is given by the formula <m>r = \frac{\Delta}{s}</m>, where <m>s</m> is the semiperimeter.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                <p>
                    Using Heron's formula, rewrite the formula for the inradius of a triangle in terms of its sides <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> and the semiperimeter <m>s</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using Heron's formula, we have
                    <md>
                        \Delta = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}.
                    </md>
                    Therefore, the inradius can be expressed as
                    <md>
                        r = \frac{\sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}}{s}.
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Hence find the inradius of a triangle with sides <m>7</m>, <m>15</m>, and <m>20</m> cm.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex2">
                    <caption>Scalene triangle with sides <m>7</m>, <m>15</m>, <m>20</m> cm and its incircle.</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.3]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B}
                                \tkzDefShiftPoint[B](150:7){A}
                                \tkzInterCC[R](B,15)(A,20)\tkzGetPoints{X}{C}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below left](B,A){$7$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below right](B,C){$20$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[above](A,C){$15$ cm}
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        For the triangle with sides <m>7</m>, <m>15</m>, and <m>20</m> cm, we have
                        <md>
                            s = \frac{7+15+20}{2} = 21 \text{ cm},
                        </md>
                        so
                        <md>
                            <mrow>r \amp =  \frac{\sqrt{21(21-7)(21-15)(21-20)}}{21} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =  \frac{\sqrt{21 \times 14 \times 6 \times 1}}{21} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =  \frac{\sqrt{1764}}{21} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =  \frac{42}{21} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 2 \text{ cm} </mrow> 
                        </md>
                        Thus the inradius is <m>2</m> cm.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-triangle-centres">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the incenter, the centroid, and the orthocentre of this triangle, plotting them on the same diagram.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-triangle-centres-given">
                <caption>A scalene triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 8/0/C, -1/4/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Each centre is the common meeting point of three construction lines:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>the <term>incentre</term> <m>I</m> is where the three <em>angle bisectors</em> meet (dashed teal);</p></li>
                <li><p>the <term>centroid</term> <m>G</m> is where the three <em>medians</em> meet (solid blue) — each median joins a vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side;</p></li>
                <li><p>the <term>orthocentre</term> <m>H</m> is where the three <em>altitudes</em> meet (dotted red) — each altitude runs from a vertex perpendicular to the opposite side. Notice how in this obtuse triangle the orthocentre lies outside the triangle.</p></li> 
            </ul>
            <figure xml:id="fig-triangle-centres-soln">
                <caption>The incentre <m>I</m> (angle bisectors), centroid <m>G</m> (medians), and orthocentre <m>H</m> (altitudes), constructed on the same scalene triangle.</caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 8/0/C, -1/4/A}
                            %% --- CALCULATE: the three centres ---
                            \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{G}
                            \tkzDefTriangleCenter[ortho](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{H}
                            %% --- CALCULATE: feet for the construction lines ---
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ma}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{Mb}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mc}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,I)(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ba}
                            \tkzInterLL(B,I)(A,C)\tkzGetPoint{Bb}
                            \tkzInterLL(C,I)(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Bc}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](A)\tkzGetPoint{Ha}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](B)\tkzGetPoint{Hb}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](C)\tkzGetPoint{Hc}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[blue, thin](A,Ma B,Mb C,Mc)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[teal, semithick, densely dashed](A,Ba B,Bb C,Bc)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(B,Ha B,Hc)
                            \tkzDrawLines[red, thin, dotted, add=0 and 0.6](A,Ha Hb,B C,Hc)
                            %% --- MARK ---
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.14, red](A,Ha,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.14, red](B,Hb,A)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.14, red](C,Hc,B)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzDrawPoint[teal, size=3pt](I)
                            \tkzDrawPoint[blue, size=3pt](G)
                            \tkzDrawPoint[red, size=3pt](H)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left, teal](I){$I$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right, blue](G){$G$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above, xshift=-3pt, red](H){$H$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each triangle below, use a pair of compasses and a straightedge to construct the <term>inscribed circle</term>. In your solution, show your construction: bisect two of the angles to locate the incentre <m>I</m>, drop a perpendicular from <m>I</m> to one side to obtain the radius, and then draw the circle.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>Acute scalene triangle.</p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-a">
                            <caption>Acute scalene triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/3.6/A}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Right triangle</p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-b">
                            <caption>Right triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Obtuse triangle.</p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-c">
                            <caption>Obtuse triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Equilateral triangle.</p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-d">
                            <caption>Equilateral triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    In each case the two angle bisectors (dashed) meet at the incentre <m>I</m>; the perpendicular from <m>I</m> to side <m>BC</m> is the inradius, and the circle is drawn with centre <m>I</m> and that radius. The incentre always lies <em>inside</em> the triangle.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the triangle:
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-a-sol">
                            <caption>Incircle of the acute scalene triangle.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/3.6/A}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterLL(A,I)(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Da}
                                        \tkzInterLL(B,I)(A,C)\tkzGetPoint{Db}
                                        \tkzInterLL(C,I)(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Dc}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](A,Da B,Db C,Dc)
                                        \tkzDrawSegment[teal](I,X)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[teal,thick](I,X)
                                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](I,X,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,X)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](I){$I$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the triangle:
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-b-sol">
                            <caption>Incircle of the right triangle.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterLL(A,I)(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Da}
                                        \tkzInterLL(B,I)(A,C)\tkzGetPoint{Db}
                                        \tkzInterLL(C,I)(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Dc}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](A,Da B,Db C,Dc)
                                        \tkzDrawSegment[teal](I,X)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[teal,thick](I,X)
                                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](I,X,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,X)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](I){$I$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the triangle:
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-c-sol">
                            <caption>Incircle of the obtuse triangle.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterLL(A,I)(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Da}
                                        \tkzInterLL(B,I)(A,C)\tkzGetPoint{Db}
                                        \tkzInterLL(C,I)(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Dc}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](A,Da B,Db C,Dc)
                                        \tkzDrawSegment[teal](I,X)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[teal,thick](I,X)
                                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](I,X,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,X)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[above right](I){$I$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the triangle:
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-build-inc-d-sol">
                            <caption>Incircle of the equilateral triangle.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterLL(A,I)(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Da}
                                        \tkzInterLL(B,I)(A,C)\tkzGetPoint{Db}
                                        \tkzInterLL(C,I)(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Dc}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](A,Da B,Db C,Dc)
                                        \tkzDrawSegment[teal](I,X)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[teal,thick](I,X)
                                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](I,X,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,X)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](I){$I$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle has a perimeter of <m>36</m> cm and an inscribed circle of radius <m>3</m> cm. Find the area of the triangle.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The semi-perimeter is <m>s = 36/2 = 18</m> cm. Using <m>\Delta = r \cdot s</m>:
                    <md>
                        \Delta = 3 \times 18 = 54 \text{ cm}^2.
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the inradius of a triangle with sides <m>6</m> cm, <m>8</m> cm, and <m>10</m> cm.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex1">
                    <caption>Right triangle with sides <m>6</m>, <m>8</m>, <m>10</m> cm and its incircle.</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$6$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$8$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$10$ cm}
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Since the triangle is right-angled:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp= \frac{6+8+10}{2} = 12 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\Delta \amp= \tfrac{1}{2}\times 6 \times 8 = 24 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>r \amp= \frac{24}{12} = 2 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangular plot of land in Kiambu has sides <m>30</m> m, <m>40</m> m, and <m>50</m> m. A farmer wants to install a circular irrigation pond that fits inside the plot and just touches all three boundaries. Find the radius of the pond.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-30-40-50">
                <caption>The triangular plot with sides <m>30</m> m, <m>40</m> m, <m>50</m> m. The inscribed circle represents the irrigation pond of radius <m>10</m> m.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$30$ m}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$40$ m}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$50$ m}
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>s \amp= \frac{30+40+50}{2} = 60 \text{ m}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\Delta \amp= \tfrac{1}{2}\times 30 \times 40 = 600 \text{ m}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp= \frac{600}{60} = 10 \text{ m}</mrow>
                </md>
                The pond should have a radius of <m>10</m> m.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The incircle of a triangle has radius <m>4</m> cm, and the triangle has perimeter <m>48</m> cm. Find the area of the triangle.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex3">
                    <caption>A triangle with incircle of radius <m>r</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 1.2/3.5/A}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        s = \frac{48}{2} = 24 \text{ cm}, \qquad \Delta = r \cdot s = 4 \times 24 = 96 \text{ cm}^2.
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has sides <m>5</m> cm, <m>12</m> cm, and <m>13</m> cm.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Find the inradius.</li>
                    <li>The incircle touches side <m>PR</m> cm at point <m>Z</m>. Find the length <m>PZ</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-5-12-13">
                <caption>Triangle <m>PQR</m> with <m>PQ = 5</m>, <m>PR = 12</m>, <m>QR = 13</m>. </caption>
                <image width="80%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/Q, 12/0/R, 0/5/P}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](P,Q,R)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](R,Q,P)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](P)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](R)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](Q,P){$5$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](Q,R){$13$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](P,R){$12$ cm}
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](P,Q,R)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto Q--R](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto P--Q](I)\tkzGetPoint{Y}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto P--R](I)\tkzGetPoint{Z}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(I,X,Y,Z)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](Y)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below](X)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](Z)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Give that the triangle is right-angled:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>s \amp= \frac{5+12+13}{2} = 15 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\Delta \amp= \tfrac{1}{2}\times 5 \times 12 = 30 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                            <mrow>r \amp= \frac{30}{15} = 2 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Since <m>PY</m> and <m>PZ</m> are both tangent to the incircle and meet at the common point <m>P</m>, they are equal. To find <m>PY</m> we can subtract <m>QY</m> from <m>PQ</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p> Since <m>\triangle PQR</m> is right angled, <m>\angle IXQ = \angle IYQ = 90^\circ</m>, and <m>YI = IX = r</m>, <m>YIXW</m> is a square.
                    </p>
                    <p>  Hence <m>QY = r = 2</m>, and so <m>PZ = PY = 5 - 2 = 3</m> cm.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A right triangle has legs <m>5</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Calculate <m>\dfrac{a+b-c}{2}</m>.</li>
                        <li>Compute <m>r = \frac{\Delta}{s}</m>, and compare to your answer from (a).</li>
                        <li>Simplify <m>(a+b+c)(a+b-c)</m> if <m>a^2 + b^2 = c^2</m>.</li>
                        <li>Hence prove that <m>r = \dfrac{a+b-c}{2}</m> for right angled triangles.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex5">
                    <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>5</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm and its incircle.</caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/Q, 12/0/R, 0/5/P}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(P,Q,R)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](R,Q,P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above left](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](R)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[left](Q,P){$5$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below](Q,R){$12$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[right](P,R){$13$ cm}
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](P,Q,R)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto Q--R](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The hypotenuse is <m>c = \sqrt{5^2+12^2} = \sqrt{169} = 13</m> cm.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{5+12-13}{2} = \dfrac{4}{2} = 2</m> cm.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>s = \dfrac{5+12+13}{2} = 15</m> cm, <m>\Delta = \tfrac{1}{2}\times 5 \times 12 = 30</m> cm<m>^2</m>, so <m>r = 30/15 = 2</m> cm. This is the same as the result from (a).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Expanding:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> (a+b+c)(a+b-c) \amp = (a+b)^2 - c^2 </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = a^2 + 2ab + b^2 - c^2 </mrow>
                            <mrow number="yes" xml:id="ABC"> (a+b+c)(a+b-c)\amp = 2ab </mrow>
                        </md>
                        where we relied on the fact that <m>a^2 + b^2 = c^2 </m>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p> The area of a right-angled triangle is <m>\frac{1}{2}ab</m>, so:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> r \amp = \frac{\Delta}{s} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{\frac{1}{2}ab}{\frac{a+b+c}{2}} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{ab}{a+b+c} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            Using <xref ref="ABC"/>, <m>\frac{1}{a+b+c} = \frac{a+b-c}{2ab}</m>, so:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp = ab \times \frac{a+b-c}{2ab} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{a+b-c}{2} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            as required.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each triangle below, use a pair of compasses and a straightedge to construct the inscribed circle.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>Acute scalene triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a1">
                                <caption>Acute scalene triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 1/3.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Right triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a2">
                                <caption>Right triangle <m>ABC</m> with the right angle at <m>B</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Obtuse triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a3">
                                <caption>Obtuse triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Equilateral triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a4">
                                <caption>Equilateral triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    In each case, bisect two angles to find the incenter <m>I</m>, then drop a perpendicular to one side to find the inradius, and draw the circle.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li> Drawing the figure:
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a1">
                                <caption>Acute scalene triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 1/3.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li> Drawing the figure:
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a2">
                                <caption>Right triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li> Drawing the figure:
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a3">
                                <caption>Obtuse triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li> Drawing the figure:
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a4">
                                <caption>Equilateral triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-incentre-angle">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Triangle <m>ABC</m> has <m>\angle A = 50^\circ</m>, <m>\angle B = 60^\circ</m>, and <m>\angle C = 70^\circ</m>. 
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incentre-angle-50-60-70">
                    <caption>Triangle ABC</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                %% --- SET: build the 50-60-70 triangle from its angles ---
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){B}\tkzDefPoint(6,0){C}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center B angle 60](C)\tkzGetPoint{B60}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center C angle -70](B)\tkzGetPoint{C70}
                                \tkzInterLL(B,B60)(C,C70)\tkzGetPoint{A}
                                %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                %% --- DRAW ---
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](A,B,C)

                                \tkzMarkAngles(C,B,A A,C,B B,A,C)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.5](C,B,A){$60^\circ$}
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.5](A,C,B){$70^\circ$}
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.5](B,A,C){$50^\circ$}
                                %% --- LABEL ---
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    Let <m>I</m> be the <term>incentre</term>.
                </p>

                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Construct (or describe how to find) the incentre <m>I</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Since <m>I</m> lies on the bisectors of angles <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>, write down <m>\angle IBC</m> and <m>\angle ICB</m>, and hence find <m>\angle BIC</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Show that for <em>any</em> triangle, <m>\angle BIC = 90^\circ + \tfrac{1}{2}\angle A</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p><m>I</m> is the intersection of the three internal angle bisectors (it is enough to construct any two).</p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-incentre-angle-50-60-70-soln1">
                    <caption>Triangle ABC</caption>
                        <image width="55%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                    %% --- SET: build the 50-60-70 triangle from its angles ---
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){B}\tkzDefPoint(6,0){C}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center B angle 60](C)\tkzGetPoint{B60}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center C angle -70](B)\tkzGetPoint{C70}
                                    \tkzInterLL(B,B60)(C,C70)\tkzGetPoint{A}
                                    %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                    %% --- DRAW ---
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C)

                                    \tkzMarkAngles(C,B,A A,C,B B,A,C)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.5](C,B,A){$60^\circ$}
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.5](A,C,B){$70^\circ$}
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.5](B,A,C){$50^\circ$}

                                    \tkzDrawLine[add=0 and 0.5](A,I)
                                    \tkzDrawLine[add=0 and 0.5](B,I)
                                    \tkzDrawLine[add=0 and 0.5](C,I)
                                    %% --- LABEL ---
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](I)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\angle IBC = \tfrac{1}{2}\angle B = 30^\circ</m> and <m>\angle ICB = \tfrac{1}{2}\angle C = 35^\circ</m>. In triangle <m>BIC</m> the angles sum to <m>180^\circ</m>, so
                                <md><mrow>\angle BIC = 180^\circ - 30^\circ - 35^\circ = 115^\circ.</mrow></md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                In general <m>\angle IBC = \tfrac{1}{2}\angle B</m> and <m>\angle ICB = \tfrac{1}{2}\angle C</m>, and <m>\angle A + \angle B + \angle C = 180^\circ</m>, so
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\angle BIC \amp = 180^\circ - \tfrac{1}{2}(\angle B + \angle C) = 180^\circ - \tfrac{1}{2}(180^\circ - \angle A)</mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 90^\circ + \tfrac{1}{2}\angle A.</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incentre-angle-soln">
                    <caption>The incentre <m>I</m>. The bisectors halve <m>\angle B</m> and <m>\angle C</m>, giving <m>\angle BIC = 90^\circ + \tfrac{1}{2}\angle A</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                %% --- SET: build the 50-60-70 triangle from its angles ---
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){B}\tkzDefPoint(6,0){C}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center B angle 60](C)\tkzGetPoint{B60}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center C angle -70](B)\tkzGetPoint{C70}
                                \tkzInterLL(B,B60)(C,C70)\tkzGetPoint{A}
                                %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                %% --- DRAW ---
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawSegments[teal, densely dashed](A,I B,I C,I)
                                \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoint[teal,size=4pt](I)
                                %% --- MARK ---
                                \tkzMarkAngles[mark=|, size=0.6](I,B,A C,B,I)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[mark=||, size=0.8](A,C,I I,C,B)
                                \tkzMarkAngle[fill=orange!25, size=0.5](B,I,C)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.75](B,I,C){$\angle BIC$}
                                %% --- LABEL ---
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[above, teal](I){$I$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-centroid-ratio">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In triangle <m>ABC</m>, let <m>M_a</m>, <m>M_b</m>, <m>M_c</m> be the midpoints of <m>BC</m>, <m>CA</m>, <m>AB</m>. The three medians <m>AM_a</m>, <m>BM_b</m>, <m>CM_c</m> meet at the <term>centroid</term> <m>G</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Construct the centroid <m>G</m> by drawing two of the medians and marking their intersection.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Measure <m>AG</m> and <m>GM_a</m>. What is the ratio <m>AG : GM_a</m>?</p></li>
                    <li><p>Prove, using coordinates (or position vectors), that the centroid divides every median in the ratio <m>2:1</m> measured from the vertex.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>Two medians are enough; the third passes through the same point <m>G</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><m>AG : GM_a = 2 : 1</m> (and likewise for the other two medians).</p></li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write the vertices as position vectors <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, <m>\mathbf{b}</m>, <m>\mathbf{c}</m>. Then <m>G = \tfrac{1}{3}(\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c})</m> and <m>M_a = \tfrac{1}{2}(\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c})</m>. So
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\vec{AG} \amp = G - \mathbf{a} = \tfrac{1}{3}(\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c}-2\mathbf{a}),</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\vec{GM_a} \amp = M_a - G = \tfrac{1}{2}(\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c}) - \tfrac{1}{3}(\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c}) = \tfrac{1}{6}(\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c}-2\mathbf{a}).</mrow>
                                </md>
                                Hence <m>\vec{AG} = 2\,\vec{GM_a}</m>, so <m>AG : GM_a = 2 : 1</m>. The same argument applies to the medians from <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-centroid-ratio-soln">
                    <caption>The three medians meet at the centroid <m>G</m>. The equal tick marks show <m>AG : GM_a = 2 : 1</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="58%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                %% --- SET ---
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 6/0/C, 1.5/4.5/A}
                                %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ma}
                                \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{Mb}
                                \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mc}
                                \tkzInterLL(A,Ma)(B,Mb)\tkzGetPoint{G}
                                \tkzDefMidPoint(A,G)\tkzGetPoint{P}
                                %% --- DRAW ---
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawSegments[blue, thin](A,Ma B,Mb C,Mc)
                                %% --- MARK ---
                                \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|, red](A,P P,G G,Ma)
                                %% --- LABEL ---
                                \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](A,B,C,Ma,Mb,Mc)
                                \tkzDrawPoint[blue,size=4pt](G)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[right, blue](G){$G$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ma){$M_a$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[above right](Mb){$M_b$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[left](Mc){$M_c$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Determine the fraction of an equilateral triangle (side length <m>x</m>) that is covered by its incircle.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    Use Heron's formula, as in <xref ref="heron-incircle"/>
                </p>
            </hint>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    For an equilateral triangle <m>\triangle ABC</m> with side length <m>x</m>, we have semiperimeter <m>s = \frac{3x}{2}</m>. Using Heron's formula, the area is:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \Delta \amp = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp= \sqrt{\frac{3x}{2}\left(\frac{3x}{2}-x\right)^3} </mrow> 
                        <mrow> \amp= \sqrt{\frac{3x}{2}\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^3} </mrow> 
                        <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{3x^4}{16}}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}x^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    The inradius is:
                    <md>
                        r = \frac{\Delta}{s} = \frac{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}x^2}{\frac{3x}{2}} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{6}x
                    </md>
                    The area of the incircle is:
                    <md>
                        \text{Area}(\text{incircle}) = \pi r^2 = \pi \left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{6}x\right)^2 = \frac{\pi}{12}x^2
                    </md>
                    Therefore, the fraction of the triangle covered by the incircle is:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{\text{Area}(\text{incircle})}{\Delta} \amp = \frac{\frac{\pi}{12}x^2}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}x^2} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{\pi \sqrt{3}}{9} </mrow>
                    </md>
                    This is approximately 0.6046, so the incircle covers about 60.46% of the area of the equilateral triangle. This is independent of the side length <m>x</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    An arbitrary triangle <m>ABC</m> is drawn below. We have created three new triangles <m>\triangle APB</m>, <m>\triangle BQC</m>, <m>\triangle CRA</m>, which are all similar to each other.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="triangle-with-triangles">
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\AP}{3.8}
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\theta}{30}
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4/2/B, 5.5/-5/C}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(A,B)\tkzGetAngle{AngAB}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(B,C)\tkzGetAngle{AngBC}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(C,A)\tkzGetAngle{AngCA}
                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngAB]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[A](\theta:\AP){P}
                                \end{scope}

                                \tkzCalcLength(A,B) \tkzGetLength{AB}
                                \tkzCalcLength(B,C) \tkzGetLength{BC}
                                \tkzCalcLength(C,A) \tkzGetLength{CA}
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\BQ}{(\AP * \BC) / \AB}
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\CR}{(\AP * \CA) / \AB}

                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngBC]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[B](\theta:\BQ){Q}
                                \end{scope}
                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngCA]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[C](\theta:\CR){R}
                                \end{scope}

                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](P,Q,R) \tkzGetPoint{O'} % This is the same as O


                                \tkzDrawSegments(A,P P,B B,Q Q,C C,R R,A)
                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=red!20, opacity=0.5](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=|](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)

                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=blue!20, opacity=0.5](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=||](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)

                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,P,Q,R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find the centroid of <m>\triangle ABC</m>, and mark it as <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p> We have marked the centroid <m>G</m> in the figure below. It is the point of concurrency of the medians of <m>\triangle ABC</m>.</p>
                    <figure xml:id="triangle-with-triangles-soln1">
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\AP}{3.8}
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\theta}{30}
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4/2/B, 5.5/-5/C}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(A,B)\tkzGetAngle{AngAB}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(B,C)\tkzGetAngle{AngBC}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(C,A)\tkzGetAngle{AngCA}
                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngAB]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[A](\theta:\AP){P}
                                \end{scope}

                                \tkzCalcLength(A,B) \tkzGetLength{AB}
                                \tkzCalcLength(B,C) \tkzGetLength{BC}
                                \tkzCalcLength(C,A) \tkzGetLength{CA}
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\BQ}{\AP * \BC / \AB}
                                \pgfmathsetmacro{\CR}{\AP * \CA / \AB}

                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngBC]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[B](\theta:\BQ){Q}
                                \end{scope}
                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngCA]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[C](\theta:\CR){R}
                                \end{scope}

                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](P,Q,R) \tkzGetPoint{O'} % This is the same as O


                                \tkzDrawSegments(A,P P,B B,Q Q,C C,R R,A)
                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=red!20, opacity=0.5](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=|](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)
                                \tkzDrawLines[add=0 and 0.5](B,O A,O C,O)

                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=blue!20, opacity=0.5](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=||](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)

                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,P,Q,R,O)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below right](O){$G$}
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    </figure>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find the centroid of <m>\triangle PQR</m>. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The centroid of <m>\triangle PQR</m> is the same point <m>G</m> as the centroid of <m>\triangle ABC</m>.
                        <figure xml:id="triangle-with-triangles-soln2">
                            <image width="70%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\AP}{3.8}
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\theta}{30}
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4/2/B, 5.5/-5/C}
                                        \tkzFindSlopeAngle(A,B)\tkzGetAngle{AngAB}
                                        \tkzFindSlopeAngle(B,C)\tkzGetAngle{AngBC}
                                        \tkzFindSlopeAngle(C,A)\tkzGetAngle{AngCA}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                        \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngAB]
                                            \tkzDefShiftPoint[A](\theta:\AP){P}
                                        \end{scope}

                                        \tkzCalcLength(A,B) \tkzGetLength{AB}
                                        \tkzCalcLength(B,C) \tkzGetLength{BC}
                                        \tkzCalcLength(C,A) \tkzGetLength{CA}
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\BQ}{(\AP * \BC) / \AB}
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\CR}{(\AP * \CA) / \AB}

                                        \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngBC]
                                            \tkzDefShiftPoint[B](\theta:\BQ){Q}
                                        \end{scope}
                                        \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngCA]
                                            \tkzDefShiftPoint[C](\theta:\CR){R}
                                        \end{scope}

                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](P,Q,R) \tkzGetPoint{O'} % This is the same as O


                                        \tkzDrawSegments(A,P P,B B,Q Q,C C,R R,A)
                                        \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=red!20, opacity=0.5](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)
                                        \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=|](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)

                                        \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=blue!20, opacity=0.5](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)
                                        \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=||](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)

                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[blue, thick](P,Q,R)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,P,Q,R,O,O')
                                        \tkzDrawLines[add=0 and 0.5](P,O' Q,O' R,O')
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below right](O){$G$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](R)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

